FragDigits should not have '-' since FragDigits is used in definition of DecimalLiteral, etc. This would work better:
  IntegerLiteral : '-'? FragDigits ;

But I think we should *not* do this now, maybe revert since it's out of scope, and we can make a separate commit for negative number support, if needed. Apologies, when I asked for test case for negative numbers, I didn't realize that the grammar doesn't support negative numbers! So it is out of scope.

please conform to teh names defined in https://raw.githubusercontent.com/antlr/grammars-v4/master/xpath/xpath31/XPath31.g4

EG : '=>' ;
GE : '>=' ;
GT : '>' ;
LT : '<' ;

Agreed. Something like this should work:
  leafCondition : AT leafName EQ StringLiteral | AT leafName comparativeOperators  IntegerLiteral ;

  comparativeOperators : ( LT | LE | EQ | GE | GT ) ;

And I think this may fix issues with AND/OR with comparisons.

you need this because you had no 'else' on line 93! I restructured the method like so and all test are passing:


        Object comparisonValue;
        if (ctx.IntegerLiteral() != null) {
            comparisonValue = Integer.valueOf(ctx.IntegerLiteral().getText());
        } else {
            if (ctx.StringLiteral() != null) {
                final boolean wasWrappedInDoubleQuote = ctx.StringLiteral().getText().startsWith("\"");
                comparisonValue = stripFirstAndLastCharacter(ctx.StringLiteral().getText());
                if (wasWrappedInDoubleQuote) {
                    comparisonValue = String.valueOf(comparisonValue).replace("'", "\\'");
                }
            } else {
                throw new PathParsingException(
                    "Unsupported comparison value encountered in expression" + ctx.getText());
            }
        }

